ANOTHER police officer was shot dead at his home in Old Payne location in Mthatha on Friday night, 18 June. He was robbed of his service pistol in the process. Police in the Eastern Cape has sent its condolences to the family, friends and relatives of Mphakameli Mazinywana. Preliminary investigation, according to police spokesman Brigadier Tembinkosi Kinana, indicates that Mazinywana (48) who was stationed at Mthatha Central, was at his house together with his wife when unknown suspects kicked the door and demanded a firearm from the officer. They shot him on the upper body, took his service firearm and escaped. “The member succumbed to gunshot injuries,” said Kinana. He said the motive for the attack was currently under investigation. A case of murder and house robbery has been registered. No arrest made at this stage. Eastern Cape police commissioner, Lieutenant-General Liziwe Ntshinga has expressed shock at the incident. She immediately sent condolences to the family of the deceased member who she described as one of the “loyal and dedicated foot soldiers” of the South African Police Service in crime investigations. “The SAPS has lost a hero, a father and servant of the community. We are devastated as the SAPS family, but we shall find the culprits alive.” said Lt Gen Ntshinga Anyone with information that can lead to the arrest of the suspects who are still at large, is requested to make contact with Mthatha Central Police or call the CrimeStop on 086 00 10111.